  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Assessing customer risk profiles\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Implementing internal controls\n- Conducting employee training\n- Regular risk assessments\n\n4. Know Your Customer (KYC) Procedures\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Conducting background checks\n- Ongoing customer monitoring\n\n5. Legal Regulations\n- Compliance with Bank Secrecy Act\n- Following Financial Action Task Force (FATF) guidelines\n- Adhering to international anti-money laundering standards\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, fines, and potential criminal prosecution.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific aspects of money laundering prevention?",
